This pioneering bill would give workers the same legal opportunities for discrimination organization of trade unions and other forms of discrimination, stopping power union opponents
Changing the law on the regulation of labor relations so as to allow workers experiencing discrimination for participation in the organization of trade unions, to seek justice in civil courts - and receive compensation for damages and punitive payments - a sensible and necessary initiative.
However, it is certainly not the radical initiative - at least by American standards.
In fact, the best way to understand that offer Ellison, Lewis and co-authors of the bill is to remember a very American idea.
Despite the drubbing that the unions have been in recent years - in Wisconsin, Michigan and other states across the country - the Americans once supported countries around the world to adopt, expand and respect for human rights.
There was a time that still remember the millions of Americans, when this country simultaneously defended the democracy, freedom of speech, freedom of the press and the right to organize.
When the United States occupied Japan after World War II, General Douglas MacArthur and his assistants have helped the country to adopt the constitution, compiled so as to ensure that militarized autocracy Hideki той was replaced by democracy.
Fully aware that workers and their unions play a role in the formation of a new Japan, they included a text that explicitly acknowledged that "the right of workers to organize, and for negotiations, and the collective action is guaranteed."
When the United States occupied Germany after World War II, General Dwight David Eisenhower and his assistants have helped the Germans to write a constitution that guaranteed that the fascism of Adolf Hitler was replaced by a strong democracy.
Recognizing that workers will have to organize themselves and be heard in the new state, the Germans have included an article that openly stated: "The right to form associations to protect and improve labor and economic conditions will be guaranteed to every man and every profession or activity.
Agreements that restrict or seek to curtail this right will not have legal force; measures aimed at these goals will be recognized as illegal.
When former first lady Eleanor Roosevelt was the chairman of the International Commission on Human Rights, which amounted to the Universal Declaration of Human Rights, which in 1948 will be adopted by the United Nations as a global agreement, Roosevelt and the compilers have included a guarantee that "everyone has the right to organize and join trade unions for the protection of their interests."
Generations of Americans take for granted the basic position that labor rights are human rights.
When this country advised by other countries on how to create a civil and democratic society, Americans have explained that the right to organize unions - and to this union participated as an equal partner in collective bargaining with corporations and government agencies - must be protected.
Now that these rights are attacked in America, wisely, indeed, return to the American ideal that working people should have the right to organize and to make their voices heard in a free and open society.
The Reverend Martin Luther King, Jr. said fifty years ago:
The story is a great teacher.
Now everyone knows that the trade union movement has not undermined the forces of the nation, but increased them.
Raising the living standards of millions, the unions miraculously created the market for the industry and raised a whole nation to do the level of production.
Those who are attacking the unions, forget these simple truths, but history remembers them.
History remembers how should and to us.
The official recognition of labour rights as human rights - and the expansion of the protection of civil rights to prevent discrimination against union organization is long overdue.
Keith Ellison and John Lewis So the ideals that historically expanded America and made the promise of democracy a reality.
