The deputies offered to accelerate the entry into force of the law on personal data
In the case of the success of the initiative, the Russians cannot be stored on servers abroad from January 1, 2015
In the State Duma introduced a draft law providing for the date of entry into force already adopted the law on the personal data of Russians - from September 1, 2016 on January 1, 2015.
The initiative is posted on the basis of the legislative activities of the lower house.
Its authors were deputies of the State Duma, Vadim Dengin, Yaroslav Nilov (LDPR), Yevgeny Fyodorov ("United Russia"), Vladimir Parakhin ("Just Russia") and Alexander Yushchenko (KPRF).
Such a change, according to the initiative, will contribute to a more reliable and efficient provision of the rights of citizens of the Russian Federation on the safety of personal data and the protection of privacy of correspondence in information and telecommunication networks.
The law, which the entry into force of the hurry parliamentarians, obliges store on the territory of the Russian Federation the personal data of Russians that are processed through the Internet.
He also makes mandatory recording, systematization, accumulation, storage, refining and extraction of personal data of citizens of the Russian Federation, in databases located on the territory of Russia, as well as the information about the location of such databases.
In addition, the law gives Roskomnadzor right on the basis of the court's decision to restrict access to information in violation of the laws of the Russian Federation in the field of personal data.
The law also proposes the creation of the so-called "black sites" lists-violators - automated information system "Reestr rights violators of personal data."
This law was passed by the State Duma in the summer.
The authors of the bill were Andrei Lugovoi and Vadim Dengin from the LDPR and Alexander Yushchenko from the Communist Party.
Dengin and Yushchenko also are one of the authors of the current bill of the entry into force of the already adopted law.
Those who have data centers in the Russian Federation does not have to pay for rent
Commenting on the bill introduced by today in the State Duma, the first deputy head of the Duma Committee for Information Policy Leonid Levin said he sees no problems to move the date of entry into force of the law on the protection of personal data.
He said that those companies that by January 1, 2015, will not have their own repositories of personal data of Russians on the territory of the Russian Federation, will be able to rent them, for example, "Rostelecom, who has repeatedly said that they are ready to provide their servers in rent and already provides its servers, the Mail Group, the Western companies that now provide their servers."
"Besides, there are several independent data centers that are ready to cooperate in this area," he added.
"If the company will take the decision to execute the law and continue to work on the territory of the Russian Federation, does not see a problem - they will receive technological possibilities for placement," Levin concluded.
Controversial the bill
Immediately after the publication of the draft law of the Russian Association of Electronic Communications expressed the fear that if the bill Russians will no longer be able to use many of the global Internet services.
In particular, it is about the services of online booking flights and hotels.
According to the association, "the bill deprives subjects of personal data of citizens of the Russian Federation - the right to dispose of their own data imperatively determining that their entry, systematization, etc should provide only in databases located on the territory of the Russian Federation."
In a national statement stressed that a more effective measure would be to create a mechanism of informing the user, where is the record, systematization of his personal data.
In this case, he will be able to choose at what territory will be specified actions.
The same similar bills on the "localization" of personal data in other countries resulted in the care of global services and for significant economic losses.
